<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Like that surely is just as cruel.

753
00:33:55.500 --> 00:33:57.480
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah, it does uh.

754
00:33:57.599 --> 00:34:06.839
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah, it's not our, it doesn't sit, it does not seem to fit in the theme of the, the, harmony with nature, right?

755
00:34:06.839 --> 00:34:09.000
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Um, that outbound kind of bushes.

756
00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:10.079
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: I agree.

757
00:34:10.079 --> 00:34:11.400
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: It feels kind of strange.

758
00:34:11.400 --> 00:34:13.619
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Um, if it went somewhere else.

759
00:34:13.619 --> 00:34:17.519
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: I don't know, a fish rescue centre.

760
00:34:17.519 --> 00:34:19.800
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: I don't know what, something like that maybe, but.

761
00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:22.199
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I'm not sure how why you would be rescuing them by fishing them up though.

762
00:34:20.159 --> 00:34:22.860
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: I don't know research.

763
00:34:22.199 --> 00:34:25.320
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: This is the thing like the fishing is the problem.

764
00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:26.639
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: surely with fishing.

765
00:34:26.639 --> 00:34:31.139
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Like, I've always, I mean, this is just, okay, no, I'm not going to say that.

766
00:34:31.139 --> 00:34:31.502
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I'm going to leave.

767
00:34:32.300 --> 00:34:35.300
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: I'll say this, fish are delicious.

768
00:34:35.300 --> 00:34:37.460
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: I like fish tea.

769
00:34:38.599 --> 00:34:40.639
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: I'm just saying.

770
00:34:40.639 --> 00:34:41.719
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: I also like fish.

771
00:34:41.719 --> 00:34:43.639
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: You know, I have some goldfish.

772
00:34:43.639 --> 00:34:52.639
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: That's fine, but, um, it's not the same as fishing it out of the lake, ever, and putting it in a small little tank in your RV.

773
00:34:52.639 --> 00:34:53.900
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Um,

774
00:34:53.500 --> 00:35:00.002
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Yeah, I just, I, it's, it seems, it seems like a weird decision to be like, oh, we don't want you to eat the fish, but we do want...

775
00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:02.502
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: What?

776
00:35:02.500 --> 00:35:10.002
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Anyway, if you really want fishing, there you go, you got your fishing and your camper van.

777
00:35:05.500 --> 00:35:06.502
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: There.

778
00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:11.502
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Except not fish.

779
00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:20.800
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Next up, Sunhaven have released a 3.one update, and this is a quality of life improvements update.

780
00:35:20.800 --> 00:35:23.380
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: They have added repairable items.

781
00:35:23.500 --> 00:35:24.502
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: That's good.

782
00:35:23.679 --> 00:35:28.502
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: They have added a pop-up when you gain a new recipe.

783
00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:30.500
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: That's also good.

784
00:35:30.500 --> 00:35:32.502
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: They've also added credits to the game.

785
00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:34.679
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: That's really good.

786
00:35:34.800 --> 00:35:37.019
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: That's so good.

787
00:35:37.019 --> 00:35:38.820
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: It should have been there from the start.

788
00:35:38.500 --> 00:35:47.079
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: It sounds like they actually, it sounded like, actually, I'm not sure if the credits existed in the game at all, because the 1st one has added the credits button to the main menu.

789
00:35:38.820 --> 00:35:40.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: That feels very...

790
00:35:47.079 --> 00:35:50.619
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: And then there's added team credits and added community credits.

791
00:35:47.500 --> 00:35:48.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Okay.

792
00:35:50.619 --> 00:35:54.002
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: So that does make it sound like there were no credits full stop.

793
00:35:54.500 --> 00:36:02.840
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: I will be, to give the generous interpretation, there have been more people who have helped out, so they're adding credits to the credits.

794
00:36:02.840 --> 00:36:04.760
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: But I agree with you.

795
00:36:04.760 --> 00:36:08.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: It does sound like there were no credits to begin with, which is not good.

796
00:36:06.500 --> 00:36:08.300
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Do you know, do you know?

797
00:36:08.300 --> 00:36:11.360
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Well, so here's my here's my take on credits in games.

798
00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:14.360
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I find it a little bit weird.

799
00:36:14.360 --> 00:36:22.039
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Now, I understand that credits are in games because it's kind, they're kind of treated like film TV, stuff like that.

800
00:36:22.039 --> 00:36:23.239
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: And those have credits.

801
00:36:22.500 --> 00:36:23.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Mhm.

802
00:36:23.239 --> 00:36:28.880
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: But, and this is not, this is not me saying that people should not be credited for the work, right?

803
00:36:28.880 --> 00:36:29.900
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Let me get that out there.

804
00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:29.780
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yes.

805
00:36:29.780 --> 00:36:31.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Okay.

806
00:36:30.260 --> 00:36:32.659
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: As okay.

807
00:36:33.500 --> 00:36:35.480
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yes.

808
00:36:34.280 --> 00:36:37.639
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I'm trying to be very careful with my wording here.

809
00:36:37.639 --> 00:36:39.320
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I, I,

810
00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:41.000
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah, I could tell because yeah, you're dancing here.

811
00:36:39.860 --> 00:36:45.139
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: There's, I'm all about the solidarity and the unions and the working people.

812
00:36:45.139 --> 00:36:46.699
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I just want to make it clear.

813
00:36:46.699 --> 00:36:49.340
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: This is specific to credits.

814
00:36:49.340 --> 00:37:00.139
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I find credits weird because there are very few jobs in the world where you're working on something means your name gets splattered on the end of it.

815
00:37:00.260 --> 00:37:03.199
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Film, TV games.

816
00:37:00.500 --> 00:37:01.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Sure.

817
00:37:03.199 --> 00:37:06.019
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: That's basically it, right?

818
00:37:06.019 --> 00:37:12.440
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Can you, can you imagine if every website you went to had a list of every single person that had worked on that?

819
00:37:13.500 --> 00:37:16.019
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: I guess so, eh, that would be.

820
00:37:16.019 --> 00:37:17.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Um.

821
00:37:16.380 --> 00:37:22.800
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: That, that, like, just coming from my point of view of my work, like I make websites.

822
00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:26.760
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I would find it really weird if that was a thing that happened.

823
00:37:26.760 --> 00:37:36.960
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: And obviously games tend to have credits because they're treated more like film and TV than they are treated like websites and software and stuff like that.

824
00:37:36.960 --> 00:37:45.840
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: And you know, I do get that sometimes software does also have like a credits page, but it tends to be much more limited, right?

825
00:37:37.500 --> 00:37:38.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah.

826
00:37:45.840 --> 00:37:59.400
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Like big pieces of software don't tend to because like a little indie thing will generally have the credits of the people who've worked on it because they want to put their name on it, but like big things don't tend to and they have many, many, many more people that work on a project.

827
00:37:59.400 --> 00:38:04.739
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I'm not, I don't think I'm saying that I don't think credits should exist.

828
00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:01.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Right.

829
00:38:04.739 --> 00:38:13.920
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I just find it as a concept really weird because it's really unique to one specific area of life and nobody else in their jobs gets credits.

830
00:38:13.920 --> 00:38:16.980
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: And I know the argument here is like, oh, right, fine.

831
00:38:16.980 --> 00:38:23.280
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Well, then you should work for other jobs to give credits rather than removing credits from the jobs they give them.

832
00:38:23.280 --> 00:38:28.380
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: But I don't know if I'd want my name on all the websites that I make.

833
00:38:28.500 --> 00:38:29.460
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Sure.

834
00:38:29.340 --> 00:38:35.760
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Because a lot of them are making substandard stuff.

835
00:38:35.760 --> 00:38:37.019
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: And that's not because I want to.

836
00:38:37.019 --> 00:38:38.699
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: It's not because that's what I'm trying to do.

837
00:38:38.699 --> 00:38:40.500
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: It's because like people do that.

838
00:38:40.500 --> 00:38:43.980
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: People make you make things that are bad, right?

839
00:38:43.980 --> 00:38:47.400
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: And that is also the case with games and TV and film.

840
00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:44.900
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah.

841
00:38:47.639 --> 00:38:52.500
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: And I bet there are people who are like, oh, my name has to be on this.

842
00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:48.539
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah.

843
00:38:52.500 --> 00:38:58.920
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Like, 0 my word, I can't believe my name has to be forever tied to this piece of media that's dreadful.

844
00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:53.780
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah.

845
00:38:53.780 --> 00:38:56.502
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah, there are some people use.

846
00:38:59.500 --> 00:39:04.480
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: People hide their names even or use a, you know, uh, pseudonym for the credits.

847
00:39:04.480 --> 00:39:05.380
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: It happens, yeah.

848
00:39:05.500 --> 00:39:06.219
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Oh, interesting.

849
00:39:06.219 --> 00:39:07.502
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Is that that's a thing that happened?

850
00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:09.800
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah, that's absolutely the thing that happens.

851
00:39:09.800 --> 00:39:13.579
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Um, I know it's, it's prominent in movies.

852
00:39:13.579 --> 00:39:18.139
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Um, I don't know how much that happens in in game credits, but that is a thing that happens.

853
00:39:15.500 --> 00:39:16.002
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Interesting

854
00:39:18.139 --> 00:39:19.502
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: People will use pseudonyms.

855
00:39:19.500 --> 00:39:21.119
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: But then, then what are we doing?

856
00:39:21.119 --> 00:39:22.380
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Why, what are we doing?

857
00:39:22.380 --> 00:39:29.940
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: If if some people are not even in the credits, why are we putting pretend names in the credits, they're not you're not giving credit then.

858
00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:35.159
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah, well, I mean, that's at that point, that's that person's choice, how they want to be credited, right?

859
00:39:35.159 --> 00:39:36.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Um.

860
00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:36.840
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I don't know.

861
00:39:36.840 --> 00:39:39.960
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I just like, I'm not saying we should not do this.

862
00:39:39.960 --> 00:39:41.760
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I'm not saying that.

863
00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:40.840
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Yeah.

864
00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:42.002
<v 8C4BDD3A-4510-4A99-8C76-F1B70ABE3F65>Kevin: Well.

865
00:39:41.760 --> 00:39:46.440
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I don't want people to come at me and say, I can't believe you're saying that people shouldn't get credit for what they make.

866
00:39:46.440 --> 00:39:47.639
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I'm not saying that.

867
00:39:47.639 --> 00:39:51.480
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: I'm saying I find credit's weird, just as a concept.

868
00:39:51.480 --> 00:39:52.380
<v C06D3439-3D87-4C31-96F6-8AFF5C235318>Al: Weird.

